{"key":"post-10187470","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>10187470</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;but an alkaline PH 7-8 is good for primordia-&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Not so.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Most mushroom species prefer an acidic substrate, as do most molds.&amp;nbsp; The ONLY reason we lime casing layers is to make them less hospitable to mold spore germination, since the casing layer usually doesn't fully colonize.&amp;nbsp; Established mycelium, whether mold or mushroom, can &lt;i&gt;tolerate&lt;/i&gt; a high pH.&amp;nbsp; It's only the spores that are inhibited from germination in a basic pH environment.&amp;nbsp; Primordia are not stimulated by high pH.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;No bulk substrate ingredient is really any better than any other, if you take into account the species you're growing.&amp;nbsp; Mushrooms like worm castings and they like coffee.&amp;nbsp; They also like straw, dung, coir, etc., and perhaps best is to mix them all together in any quantity that you have them.&amp;nbsp; It also helps to cut bulk substrates with vermiculite at up to 50% of the total substrate by volume.&amp;nbsp; You don't lime substrates or worry about pH.&amp;nbsp; You only lime casing layers for reasons stated above.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>10187540</next>\n<prev>10187315</prev>\n<first>10187315</first>\n<last>10187540</last>\n<when>1240028573</when>\n<utime>04/18/09 07:22 AM</utime>\n</post>"}